1️⃣ Decoder-Only Transformer Architecture
What is a Transformer?

A Transformer is a neural network that processes sequences using attention, not recurrence (no RNNs, no LSTMs).

It consists of:

Attention layers
Feed-forward layers
Residual connections
Layer normalization
Encoder vs Decoder vs Decoder-Only
Architecture	Used for
Encoder	Understanding (classification, embeddings)
Decoder	Generation
Encoder-Decoder	Translation, summarization
Decoder-Only	Autoregressive text generation

Modern LLMs use decoder-only architecture.

Why Decoder-Only?

Because language generation is naturally:

“Given previous words, predict the next word.”

This is called autoregressive modeling.

Internal Structure of a Decoder Block

Each decoder block contains:

Masked Self-Attention
Feed Forward Network
Residual Connections
Layer Normalization
Masked Attention (VERY IMPORTANT)

When predicting token t, the model must not see tokens t+1, t+2...

Example sentence:

"I am learning transformers"

When predicting "learning", model can attend to:

"I", "am"

❌ It cannot attend to "transformers"

This is enforced using a causal mask.

Why this matters
Prevents cheating during training
Enables left-to-right generation
Makes streaming text generation possible

This architecture is used by GPT-style models

2️⃣ Pretraining (Foundation Phase)
What is Pretraining?

Pretraining is training the model on massive unlabeled text data using next-token prediction.

There are:

No instructions
No humans guiding answers
No alignment goals

Just raw text

Training Objective (Mathematically)

The model learns:

P(token_n | token_1, token_2, ..., token_n-1)

Which means:

Predict the next token given all previous tokens.

Example

Training data:

"The sun rises in the east"

Training pairs:

"The" → "sun"
"The sun" → "rises"
"The sun rises" → "in"
...

This happens billions of times.

What the model learns during pretraining

Without being explicitly taught, the model learns:

Grammar
Syntax
Semantic meaning
World facts
Cause–effect patterns
Reasoning structures

Pretraining = learning language structure + world knowledge

What it does NOT learn

❌ How to follow instructions
❌ How to be helpful
❌ What humans prefer

That comes later.

3️⃣ Instruction Tuning (Turning Model into Assistant)
Problem with Pretrained Models

A pretrained model behaves like:

“Continue the text in a statistically likely way”

Example:

User: Explain gravity
Model: Gravity is a force that was discovered...

This is not guaranteed to:

Be correct
Be concise
Follow user intent
What is Instruction Tuning?

Instruction tuning fine-tunes the pretrained model on datasets like:

Instruction → Ideal Answer

Example:

Instruction: Explain gravity simply
Answer: Gravity is the force that pulls objects toward each other...
What changes after instruction tuning?
Before	After
Text completer	Assistant
Random continuation	Intent-aware
No formatting	Structured answers
No task understanding	Task following

Instruction tuning teaches the model how to respond, not new facts.

4️⃣ RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback)
Why Instruction Tuning Is Still Not Enough

Even after instruction tuning, models can:

Hallucinate
Be overconfident
Answer unsafe questions
Sound rude or dismissive

We need human alignment.

What is RLHF?

RLHF aligns model outputs with human preferences.

Humans judge:

Which answer is better
Which is safer
Which is clearer
RLHF Pipeline (Conceptual)
Step 1: Generate Multiple Answers

Model generates several responses to the same prompt.

Step 2: Human Ranking

Humans rank answers:

Best → Good → Bad → Dangerous
Step 3: Reward Model Training

A reward model learns:

Which answers humans prefer

The main model is then optimized to maximize reward.

What RLHF Teaches

RLHF teaches:

Politeness
Honesty
Safety boundaries
Helpfulness
Uncertainty handling

RLHF does NOT teach facts
RLHF teaches behavior and values

5️⃣ GPT vs BERT (Deep Comparison)
Core Difference
Feature	GPT	BERT
Architecture	Decoder-only	Encoder-only
Attention	Masked (causal)	Bidirectional
Training	Next-token prediction	Masked language modeling
Strength	Generation	Understanding
Attention Difference (Key Insight)
GPT Attention
I → love → AI → ?

Each token sees only previous tokens.

BERT Attention
I ←→ love ←→ AI

Every token sees all others.

Why BERT Is Bad at Generation

Because:

It sees future tokens during training
It was never trained to predict next token sequentially

Therefore:
❌ BERT cannot naturally generate text

This is why:

GPT → Chatbots
BERT → Search, classification, embeddings
6️⃣ Why Fine-Tuning Isn’t Default (CRITICAL INTERVIEW TOPIC)
What is Fine-Tuning?

Updating all model weights on task-specific data.

Why NOT fine-tune by default?
1️⃣ Catastrophic Forgetting

Model forgets general knowledge when trained on narrow data.

2️⃣ Extremely Expensive

Large models require:

Huge GPUs
Long training times
Massive cost
3️⃣ Overfitting Risk

Model becomes too specialized.

4️⃣ Maintenance Problem

Every task → new model version.

What Is Used Instead?
Method	Why
Prompt engineering	Cheap, flexible
RAG	Adds fresh knowledge
LoRA / PEFT	Lightweight tuning
System prompts	Behavior control

Fine-tuning is used only when behavior must permanently change

7️⃣ Full Training Pipeline (Big Picture)
Raw Text
   ↓
Pretraining (Language Learning)
   ↓
Instruction Tuning (Task Following)
   ↓
RLHF (Human Alignment)
   ↓
Deployed Assistant


“Modern LLMs use decoder-only Transformers trained via autoregressive pretraining to learn language structure. Instruction tuning aligns them to follow user intent, while RLHF aligns responses with human preferences and safety. Full fine-tuning is avoided by default due to cost, catastrophic forgetting, and scalability issues.”
